  "prompt": "Why is rhinovirus harmful? How can it be treated?",
  "response": "Rhinovirus is one of the most common viral agents responsible for the common cold. While it is generally not harmful in a severe or life-threatening way, it can cause discomfort and various symptoms that can impact daily activities. The virus primarily affects the upper respiratory tract, leading to symptoms such as:\n\n- Runny or stuffy nose\n- Sneezing\n- Sore throat\n- Coughing\n- Headaches\n- Mild body aches\n- Low-grade fever (occasionally)\n\nRhinovirus can be more problematic for people with weakened immune systems, existing respiratory conditions like asthma, or in very young children and elderly adults.\n\n### Treatment:\nSince rhinovirus infections are viral, antibiotics (which target bacteria) are ineffective. Treatment focuses on alleviating symptoms and supporting the body's immune response:\n\n1. **Rest:** Adequate sleep and rest help the immune system combat the virus.\n2. **Hydration:** Drinking fluids like water, herbal tea, and broths keeps the body hydrated and helps loosen mucus.\n3. **Over-the-Counter Medications:** Non-prescription remedies can help manage symptoms.\n   - **Decongestants:** These reduce nasal congestion.\n   - **Antihistamines:** These can help reduce runny nose and sneezing.\n   - **Pain relievers:** Acetaminophen or ibuprofen can alleviate headaches and body aches.\n   - **Cough suppressants or expectorants:** Depending on whether the cough is dry or productive.\n\n4. **Home Remedies:** Warm salt water gargles can soothe a sore throat, and using a humidifier can help alleviate respiratory discomfort.\n5. **Good Hygiene Practices:** Frequent handwashing and disinfecting surfaces help prevent the spread of the virus.\n\n### Prevention:\nTo reduce the likelihood of contracting or spreading rhinovirus:\n- Wash hands regularly with soap and water.\n- Avoid close contact with infected individuals.\n- Disinfect commonly touched surfaces.\n- Practice respiratory etiquette (covering mouth and nose when sneezing/coughing).\n\nWhile rhinovirus typically resolves on its own within a week to 10 days, seek medical advice if symptoms worsen or if there are concerns about complications.",
